        "title": "See also"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "FFT (Fast Fourier Transform) refers to a way the discrete Fourier\nTransform (DFT) can be calculated efficiently, by using symmetries in the\ncalculated terms.  The symmetry is highest when "
              },
              {
                "kind": "code",
                "text": "n"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " is a power of 2, and\nthe transform is therefore most efficient for these sizes."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "The DFT is defined, with the conventions used in this implementation, in\nthe documentation for the "
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.fft.html",
                "href": "",
                "kind": "link",
                "target": "fft",
                "text": "fnp.fft"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " module."
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          }
        ],
        "title": "Notes"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "raw_kind": "citation",
            "raw_text": "CT\n\nCooley, James W., and John W. Tukey, 1965, \"An algorithm for the\nmachine calculation of complex Fourier series,\" Math. Comput.\n19: 297-301.",
            "type": "raw_block"
          }
        ],
        "title": "References"
      },
      {
        "blocks": [
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "import flopscope as fnp"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "fnp.fft.fft(fnp.exp(2j * fnp.pi * fnp.arange(8) / 8))"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "array([-2.33486982e-16+1.14423775e-17j,  8.00000000e+00-1.25557246e-15j,"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "        2.33486982e-16+2.33486982e-16j,  0.00000000e+00+1.22464680e-16j,"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "       -1.14423775e-17+2.33486982e-16j,  0.00000000e+00+5.20784380e-16j,"
              },
              {
                "kind": "output",
                "text": "        1.14423775e-17+1.14423775e-17j,  0.00000000e+00+1.22464680e-16j])"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          },
          {
            "inline": [
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": "In this example, real input has an FFT which is Hermitian, i.e., symmetric\nin the real part and anti-symmetric in the imaginary part, as described in\nthe "
              },
              {
                "external_url": "https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/generated/numpy.fft.html",
                "href": "",
                "kind": "link",
                "target": "fft",
                "text": "fnp.fft"
              },
              {
                "kind": "text",
                "text": " documentation:"
              }
            ],
            "type": "paragraph"
          },
          {
            "lines": [
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "t = fnp.arange(256)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "sp = fnp.fft.fft(fnp.sin(t))"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "freq = fnp.fft.fftfreq(t.shape[-1])"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "_ = plt.plot(freq, sp.real, freq, sp.imag)"
              },
              {
                "kind": "input",
                "prompt": ">>>",
                "text": "plt.show()"
              }
            ],
            "type": "doctest_block"
          }
        ],
